<sec>
<st>
Obesity risks (according to the Abs Diet)</st>
<p>

Researchers at the <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../445/248445.xml">
University of Massachusetts</link></university>
 analyzed the eating habits of 500 men and women and found connections between the way people eat and the risk of becoming overweight.  Below are some of the habits that can increase or decrease the risk of becoming obese.</p>
<p>

<table class="wikitable">
<row>
<header>
Habit</header>
<header>
Changes Risk of Obesity By</header>
</row>
<row>
<col>
Eating at least one midday snack</col>
<col>
&amp;minus;39 percent</col>
</row>
<row>
<col>
Eating dinner as your biggest meal of the day</col>
<col>
+ 6 percent</col>
</row>
<row>
<col>
Waiting more than 3 hours after waking up to eat breakfast</col>
<col>
+43 percent</col>
</row>
<row>
<col>
Eating more than a third of your meals in restaurants</col>
<col>
+69 percent</col>
</row>
<row>
<col>
Going to bed hungry (3 or more hours after last meal or snack)</col>
<col>
+101 percent</col>
</row>
<row>
<col>
